{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586643"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15086"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15086"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.96,0.04,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7774"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53370"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract obstruction can occur at various anatomical levels and may be either congenital or acquired. Some causes are present at birth while others develop later in life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a congenital cause of urinary tract obstruction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retroperitoneal fibrosis","Posterior urethral valves","Benign prostatic hyperplasia","Ureteric stones","Pelvic malignancy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior urethral valves\u003C/strong\u003E, which are abnormal tissue folds in the posterior urethra present at birth. These valves obstruct urinary outflow and are the most common cause of congenital bladder outlet obstruction in male infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an acquired inflammatory condition where fibrous tissue forms in the retroperitoneum, potentially compressing the ureters\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is an age-related condition that typically develops in men over 50 years\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteric stones\u003C/strong\u003E form over time due to various metabolic and environmental factors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic malignancy\u003C/strong\u003E is an acquired condition that can cause external compression of urinary structures\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly detection and treatment of posterior urethral valves is crucial to prevent complications such as bladder dysfunction, vesicoureteric reflux, and kidney damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Posterior urethral valves are the most common congenital cause of bladder outlet obstruction in male infants","Posterior urethral valves are abnormal tissue folds in the posterior urethra that obstruct urine flow","Untreated posterior urethral valves can lead to bladder dysfunction and kidney damage"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53370"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15086"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53370"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:30:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:32:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7774"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16